    "readme": "# FabLatticeGPT\n\nA custom GPT deployed and in live use by members of the Enterprise FabLab at Creative Spark. It pressure-tests early-stage product ideas *before* they reach the prototyping equipment. This repository is the design-iteration record: the v1 and v2 system prompts, what changed between them, and why.\n\n[**Link to the live GPT on ChatGPT**](https://chatgpt.com/g/g-69c3c9cb3c5c8191a4f996c885d0d7bc-fablatticegpt)\n\n*Requires a free ChatGPT login to open.*\n\n## Background\n\nI developed FabLatticeGPT following my attendance at the **OpenAI SME AI Accelerator** in Dublin (March 25th, 2026). As the Growth Manager in the Enterprise FabLab at Creative Spark, my goal is to help our members transform raw, early-stage ideas into structured, viable prototyping plans. \n\nA recurring challenge in the FabLab environment is that members often jump straight from a vague idea into implementation (e.g., asking for specific Arduino code or buying an exact pump) without having first mapped the problem space, physical constraints, and testable assumptions.\n\n## What is FabLatticeGPT?\n\nFabLatticeGPT acts as a strategic product assessment consultant—a \"gatekeeper\" for FabLab projects. It is designed to operate **exclusively in the problem space**. It will refuse to write your code or design your final product. Instead, it builds a \"lattice\" (a structural framework) to enable a structured and informed development of that individual's idea. \n\nIt does this by:\n1. Refusing to make assumptions and asking clarifying questions to define the problem space.\n2. Breaking the concept down into its core components (Feasibility, Viability, Desirability, Sustainability).\n3. Defining exactly what a minimum viable first prototype should look like and how early success should be measured before touching any fabrication equipment.\n\nNote: In principle, this tool could be extended for use for any project or idea in a pre-prototype stage, providing useful structure and reflection before action.\n\n## What changed from v1 to v2 — and why\n\nThe v1 prompt got the persona and the assessment framework right, but testing it against realistic member ideas exposed behavioural gaps. The v2 revisions all target the same failure mode: the model doing the member's thinking for them.\n\n1. **A phased interaction flow.** v1 let the model deliver the full seven-section assessment on first contact — a confident wall of text in response to a vague idea. v2 adds a strict three-phase flow (Discovery → Alignment → Assessment): first a 2–3 sentence reality check plus 1–3 focused questions, and the full assessment only once the problem space is actually defined. The instruction \"Do not deliver monologues\" is in the prompt because monologues are exactly what v1 produced.\n\n2. **A concrete pre-assessment checklist.** v1 said \"ask clarifying questions\" but never defined what *aligned* meant, so the model decided for itself when it had enough. v2 adds a \"Problem Space Map\" (drawing on d.school problem-space mapping) naming the four things that must be known before any assessment: the actual experience and user, the environment and its constraints, what success and failure look like, and the scale involved.\n\n3. **An explicit ban on suggesting components.** v1 banned \"engineering solutions\" in general terms, but the model still slipped into recommending parts. v2 names the offenders directly — \"pump models, code, wiring\" — and repeats the ban in both Phase 1 and the Component Breakdown output heading. The pump example is not hypothetical; it mirrors the exact behaviour the tool exists to prevent (see Background).\n\n4. **Closing the stated-assumptions loophole.** v1 allowed the model to \"explicitly state your assumptions before providing a full assessment\" — an escape hatch that let it proceed on guesses as long as it announced them. v2 removes it: missing detail means asking, never proceeding.\n\n5. **Minor output discipline.** The assessment structure is scoped to Phase 3 only, and Markdown formatting (bullets, bold) is mandated so assessments render consistently.\n\n## Example: what it does with a vague idea\n\nThe v2 prompt was tested against three one-line member-style ideas: an office self-watering planter, a \"smart\" bicycle helmet for commuters, and a full-size scooter to be built in a weekend. The responses are preserved in [`Instructions/v2_prompt_with_test_responses.md`](Instructions/v2_prompt_with_test_responses.md) (the original test prompts were not saved, but each idea is evident from its response).\n\nHere is the planter test — idea in, reality check, clarifying questions, no premature assessment:\n\n> You're already describing a plausible prototype category, but not a well-defined product brief yet. An office self-watering planter can mean anything from a low-maintenance desk accessory to a facilities-managed system for dozens of plants, and those lead to very different risks, costs, and prototype paths.\n>\n> Before I assess whether this is FabLab-ready, I need three specifics:\n>\n> 1. What is the actual user experience you want: a single desktop planter for one employee, or a shared office product for multiple plants/users?\n> 2. What environment will it live in: quiet desk area, reception space, meeting room, or somewhere with janitorial/access constraints?\n> 3. What does success look like, and what happens if it fails: healthier plants with near-zero user input, or just reduced watering frequency; and is failure an inconvenience, a leak risk, or a damage risk?\n>\n> Once you answer those, I'll map the concept properly and assess whether it's suitable for prototyping.\n\nNote it did not mention a single pump, sensor, or microcontroller.\n\n## Repository Contents\n\n*   `Instructions/v1_prompt.md`: The initial system prompt.\n*   `Instructions/v2_prompt.md`: The revised system prompt, as deployed.\n*   `Instructions/v2_prompt_with_test_responses.md`: The v2 prompt plus the recorded responses from the three test ideas above.\n\n**Footnote:** the system prompts address the assistant as **ColdWaterGPT** — the working name during development, preserved verbatim because these are the deployed artifacts. The published product is FabLatticeGPT.",
